article.description: Wally Szczerbiak scored 21 points and host Minnesota ended a four-game losing streak with an 88-69 victory over New Orleans.
article.headline: Minnesota cruises to victory after leading by as many as 32
article.linkText: Wolves dispatch Hornets to end 4-game losing skid
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Timberwolves emphatically ended their worst losing streak in nearly a year. Wally Szczerbiak scored 21 points and Minnesota snapped a four-game skid with an easy 88-69 victory over the New Orleans Hornets on Wednesday night. Kevin Garnett had 17 points, nine assists and seven rebounds for Northwest Division-leading Minnesota. The Timberwolves' losing streak was their worst since dropping six straight from Jan. 30 to Feb. 8 last season. The Wolves led by 32 points in the second half and didn't trail after Marko Jaric's 3-pointer put them up 14-11 midway through the first quarter. "We needed a game like this in the worst way," Minnesota coach Dwane Casey said. "It was good because it gave our starters a chance to play and not have to scratch to be in the game. It was good medicine for us." Rookie Chris Paul scored 15 points and David West added 11 for New Orleans, which had a season low in points and shot just 32.5 percent from the field. The Hornets were coming off an 89-76 victory over defending NBA champion San Antonio on Sunday and had won three of their last four coming into the game. "We just didn't meet their intensity and their pressure," New Orleans forward P.J. Brown said. "We've just got to understand that when (you) get the big win, you can't relax." The Wolves set season bests for points allowed in a game and the first half (30). "I thought our defense was the difference," Casey said. Minnesota's offense wasn't bad, either. Szczerbiak continued his hot play in December. He has been the Wolves' leading scorer in eight of their 10 games this month. He has 20 points or more in each of his last six games, the longest streak of his career. "Now I'm feeling really comfortable," he said. "Really in rhythm." Minnesota also got a lift off the bench from rookie Rashad McCants, who tied a career high with 14 points. He hadn't scored in his three previous games, going 0-of-13 from the field. "I wasn't frustrated at all," McCants said. "Just keep doing the things the coaches tell me and come to practice to work." The Wolves have won eight of their past nine games against the Hornets. Minnesota avenged an 84-80 loss to New Orleans on Nov. 23 in which the Wolves blew an 18-point lead. Minnesota raced to a 49-30 halftime lead by shooting 57.1 percent from the field and holding the Hornets to 24.4 percent. New Orleans missed its first eight field-goal attempts in the second quarter and was shooting 17.9 percent at that point. Things didn't get better for the Hornets after halftime. Szczerbiak's 3-pointer with 4:40 left in the third quarter stretched the lead to 63-34, and Trenton Hassell's reverse layup with 2:16 remaining gave Minnesota a 68-36 advantage, its largest of the game. New Orleans emptied its bench to begin the fourth quarter. "It's disappointing," Hornets coach Byron Scott said. "This still tells you how young the guys are." The Wolves, on the other hand, were glad to finally get a win under their belt. Three of their four losses during their skid were by two points or fewer. "It just felt good to put four quarters of basketball together," Garnett said.

Game notes
Minnesota guard Richie Frahm sat out his fourth straight game because of a sprained left ankle. ... Paul has scored in double figures in 23 of 25 games this season. ... Before the game, Hall of Famer Bob Lanier presented Garnett with the NBA's Community Assist Award for November for pledging $1.2 million to victims of Hurricane Katrina.
